Bow Hunter's syndrome (BHS), also known as rotational vertebral artery occlusion 
(VAO), is a rare entity in which vertebral artery is reversibly compressed due 
to rotation or extension of the head, causing vertebrobasilar insufficiency. 
Because of VAO, BHS should be considered as a possible life-threatening 
condition. Diverse aetiologies of BHS may trigger a broad spectrum of 
non-specific symptoms and may result in frequent misdiagnosis of this disorder 
in daily clinical practice. Herein, we present a case of BHS caused by 
previously non-described vascular aetiology.

